VLAN (Virtual Local Area Network)
🎯 Objective

Learn what a VLAN is, why it is used, how it works, different VLAN types, VLAN tagging, trunk ports, access ports, and why VLANs are important in enterprise networks and cloud infrastructure.

📖 What is a VLAN?

A VLAN (Virtual Local Area Network) is a logical way to divide a single physical network into multiple independent networks.

Although all computers may be connected to the same physical switch, VLANs make them behave as if they are on separate networks.

Why Do We Need VLANs?

Imagine a company with three departments:

HR
Finance
IT

Without VLANs:

                Switch
   ┌─────────────────────────┐
   │ HR  Finance  IT         │
   │ All in one LAN          │
   └─────────────────────────┘

Problems:

Everyone shares the same broadcast domain.
More unnecessary traffic.
Lower security.
Difficult management.
With VLANs
               Switch
      ┌───────────────────────┐
      │ VLAN 10 → HR          │
      │ VLAN 20 → Finance     │
      │ VLAN 30 → IT          │
      └───────────────────────┘



Each department becomes an independent logical network.

Advantages of VLANs
Reduces broadcast traffic.
Improves security.
Easier network management.
Better network performance.
Departments remain isolated.
Flexible network design.
Cost-effective compared to separate physical switches.

VLAN IDs
| VLAN ID | Example Department |
| ------- | ------------------ |
| 10      | HR                 |
| 20      | Finance            |
| 30      | IT                 |
| 40      | Sales              |

VLAN Communication

Devices in the same VLAN communicate directly.

PC1 (VLAN 10)  ↔  PC2 (VLAN 10)

Devices in different VLANs cannot communicate directly.

PC1 (VLAN 10)   ✖   PC3 (VLAN 20)

To communicate between VLANs, a router or Layer 3 switch is required. This is called Inter-VLAN Routing.

Access Port vs Trunk Port
Access Port
Belongs to a single VLAN.
Connects end devices such as PCs, printers, and servers.

Example:

PC
 │
Access Port
 │
Switch
Trunk Port
Carries traffic for multiple VLANs.
Connects switches or a switch to a router.

Example:

Switch A
     │
 Trunk Port
     │
Switch B
VLAN Tagging (IEEE 802.1Q)

A VLAN tag is added to Ethernet frames so switches know which VLAN the traffic belongs to.

Example:

Ethernet Frame
+------------------------------------+
| Destination MAC                    |
| Source MAC                         |
| VLAN Tag (802.1Q)                  |
| Data                               |
+------------------------------------+
Real-World Example

A company has:

Department	VLAN
HR	VLAN 10
Finance	VLAN 20
IT	VLAN 30
Sales	VLAN 40

Even if all devices are connected to the same switch, each department is isolated from the others unless routing is configured.

Linux Commands

Show network interfaces:

ip link

Show IP address:

ip addr

Display routing table:

ip route

Show active network connections:

ss -tun

Note: Creating and configuring VLAN interfaces on Linux is an advanced topic. We'll cover practical VLAN configuration later when you start Linux administration.


VLAN vs Subnet
| Feature                            | VLAN                           | Subnet                  |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------ | ----------------------- |
| Layer                              | Layer 2                        | Layer 3                 |
| Purpose                            | Logical separation of LAN      | IP network segmentation |
| Based On                           | MAC addresses                  | IP addresses            |
| Requires Router for Communication? | Yes (between VLANs)            | Yes (between subnets)   |
| Main Benefit                       | Security and traffic isolation | Efficient IP management |




